<subSubSection pageId="197" pageNumber="801" type="description">
<paragraph blockId="197.[1982,2576,448,876]" pageId="197" pageNumber="801">Descriptive notes. Head-body 130-175 mm, tail 105-160 mm, ear 20-30 mm, hindfoot 25-33 mm; weight 70-136 g. Fur of the Gray-tailed Ethiopian Rat is sandybrown to dull brown above, paler on flanks, and grayish white below. Tail is long (¢.93%</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="197.[1370,2576,881,1350]" pageId="197" pageNumber="801">of head-body length), gray above and below and mostly naked. Eyes have faint dark rings. Ears are large, gray, and lightly furred. Hindfeet and forefeet are white. Chromo- somal complement is 2n = 54 and FN = 54-58.</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="197" pageNumber="801" type="biology_ecology">
<paragraph blockId="197.[1370,2576,881,1350]" pageId="197" pageNumber="801">Habitat. Upland grasslands and scrub, extending marginally into moorlands,at eleva- tions of 2400-3500 m.</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="197.[1370,2576,881,1350]" box="[1371,1871,1079,1113]" pageId="197" pageNumber="801">Food and Feeding. No information.</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="197.[1370,2576,881,1350]" box="[1371,2330,1118,1152]" pageId="197" pageNumber="801">Breeding. Breedingis restricted to the wet season (May-December).</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="197.[1370,2576,881,1350]" box="[1370,2571,1157,1191]" pageId="197" pageNumber="801">Activity patterns. The Gray-tailed Ethiopian Ratis presumably nocturnal and terrestrial.</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="197.[1370,2576,881,1350]" box="[1371,2310,1197,1231]" pageId="197" pageNumber="801">Movements, Home range and Social organization. No information.</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
